    "summary": "South Korea's transition to democracy culminated in the June Democratic Struggle of 1987, a wave of mass protests that forced the ruling military government to accept direct presidential elections. For nearly three decades following the Korean War, South Korea had been governed by a succession of authoritarian leaders — Syngman Rhee, Park Chung-hee, and Chun Doo-hwan — who maintained political control through emergency decrees, censorship, and political repression while presiding over the country's rapid economic development.\n\nThe protests of June 1987 were sparked by the government's announcement that it would maintain the existing indirect election system for the presidency. Millions of citizens took to the streets across the country, representing a broad coalition of students, workers, and middle-class professionals. Facing the prospect of mass unrest ahead of the 1988 Seoul Olympics, ruling party leader Roh Tae-woo announced on June 29, 1987, the acceptance of all democratic demands, including direct presidential elections and the release of political prisoners. The June Declaration marked the effective end of authoritarian rule in South Korea and inaugurated a democratic transition that consolidated through successive peaceful transfers of power in the 1990s.",
